# Mirrors the rationale in osv-scanner.toml so Trivy and OSV-Scanner produce
# the same accepted-risk posture for this action.

# ─── False positives from Trivy 0.63 (lockfile actually has patched versions) ─
# brace-expansion lockfile resolves to 5.0.6 (patched); minimatch declares ^5.0.5
# which Trivy mistakes for the installed version. Upgrade Trivy >=0.71 to drop.
CVE-2026-45149
# ip-address lockfile resolves to 10.2.0; socks declares ^10.1.1 which Trivy
# misreads as 10.1.0. Same upstream Trivy bug.
CVE-2026-42338

# ─── undici 5.29.0 (transitive via @actions/github 6.0.1) — accepted risk ─
# This action only makes REST calls to trusted GitHub API via the @actions SDK;
# none of the undici attack vectors below are reachable. See osv-scanner.toml
# for the GHSA equivalents of these CVEs.
#
# CVE-2026-1525 — HTTP request smuggling via duplicate Content-Length
# Not exploitable: requests go to api.github.com only, with SDK-managed headers.
CVE-2026-1525
# CVE-2026-1527 — HTTP header injection / request smuggling
# Not exploitable: action does not set arbitrary user-controlled headers.
CVE-2026-1527
# CVE-2026-22036 — DoS via excessive decompression steps
# Not exploitable: GitHub API is the only counterparty; not a malicious server.
CVE-2026-22036
# CVE-2026-2229 — WebSocket permessage-deflate DoS via invalid extension param
# Not exploitable: this action never opens WebSocket connections.
CVE-2026-2229
# CVE-2026-1526 — WebSocket permessage-deflate unbounded memory consumption
# Not exploitable: this action never opens WebSocket connections.
CVE-2026-1526
